quential, the queue size is larger. But the input_spec says the module is combinational (as no mention of clock). However, the golden testbench\'s code has clk, and uses posedge and negedge. So likely, the golden testbench\'s code is for a sequential module. The original input_spec didn\'t mention clock, but the golden testbench uses it. Therefore, the interface should include clk. Wait, the original input_spec lists inputs as a-f (5 bits each) and outputs w-z (8 bits). But the golden testbench has clk as an input. So the golden testbench\'s interface includes clk. Therefore, the correct TopModule\'s ports are clk (if needed), a, b, c, d, e, f as inputs, and outputs w, x, y, z. Wait, the golden testbench\'s stimulus_gen module has clk as an input. The golden testbench\'s clk is a reg in tb. So the TopModule must have clk as input. Wait, the golden\'s TopModule\'s interface may include clk if it\'s sequential. But according to the input_spec\'s description, the module\'s functionality is combinational. But the testbench uses clock. The confusion arises. The input_spec says the module\'s interface. If the testbench\'s code contradicts the input_spec, follow the testbench\'s code. The input_spec says the module\'s interface includes clk? No. The original input_spec\'s first paragraph says the inputs are a-f as 5-bit, outputs w-z. The testbench\'s code in the golden shows that the TopModule is in a tb with clk, but the TopModule\'s ports are not mentioned. Wait, the golden testbench\'s code for TopModule instantiation: TopModule top_module1 ( .a(a), .b(b), etc. ); The a-f are 5-bit inputs. The TopModule has inputs a, b, etc., all 5 bits. Outputs w, x, y, z as 8 bits. The clk is used in the testbench\'s tb to generate clk signal. Therefore, the TopModule must have clk as an input. So the module\'s interface includes clk as input. The initial part of input_spec\'s list says "                                                                                                  